       <section id="est">
            <h2>Explaination</h2>
            <ul>
               <li> 
            <h4 >Financial Institutions:</h4>
            <p class="indent">Financial institutions include banks, credit unions, insurance companies, investment firms, and other entities that offer financial services. They play a crucial role in mobilizing funds from savers and channeling them towards borrowers and investors. Financial institutions provide services such as accepting deposits, providing loans, facilitating investments, and managing risks.
            </p>   </li>
            <li>
            <h4>Financial Markets:</h4>
            <p class="indent">Financial markets provide a platform for buying and selling financial instruments such as stocks, bonds, commodities, currencies, and derivatives. They facilitate the transfer of funds from investors to borrowers or sellers and enable price discovery and liquidity. Examples of financial markets include stock exchanges, bond markets, commodity markets, and foreign exchange markets.
            </p>
            </li>
            <li>
            <h4 >Regulatory Bodies:</h4>
            <p class="indent">Regulatory bodies are government or independent agencies responsible for overseeing and regulating the financial system. They establish and enforce rules, regulations, and standards to ensure fair and transparent practices, protect investors, maintain stability, and mitigate systemic risks. Regulatory bodies can include central banks, securities and exchange commissions, banking authorities, and insurance regulatory agencies.
            </p></li>
            <li>
            <h4>Financial Instruments:</h4>
               <p class="indent"> Financial instruments are contracts or agreements that represent a financial claim or ownership. They include stocks, bonds, options, futures, mortgages, loans, and insurance policies. These instruments allow individuals, businesses, and institutions to raise capital, manage risks, invest, and save.
               </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <h4>Central Banks:</h4>
                <p class="indent">Central banks are the primary monetary authorities in a country or a group of countries. They are responsible for formulating and implementing monetary policies, regulating banks, managing the money supply, and maintaining financial stability. Central banks also act as lenders of last resort to provide liquidity to financial institutions during times of crisis.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <h4 >Financial Services:</h4>
                <p class="indent">The range of services provided by financial institutions and professionals to individuals, businesses, and organizations. These services involve the management, investment, and allocation of financial resources, as well as the facilitation of financial transactions.</p>
            </li>
            </ul>
       </section>
       <section id="wfm">
        <h2>Financial Markets</h2>

        <p class="indent">Financial markets refer to platforms where buyers and sellers engage in trading various financial assets, such as stocks, bonds, currencies, commodities, and derivatives. These markets facilitate the allocation of capital and enable investors to buy or sell financial instruments based on their investment objectives and risk tolerance.</p>
        
        <h4>Functions of Financial Markets</h4>
        
        <ul>
        <li><p><b>Price Discovery:</b> Financial markets determine the prices of financial assets based on supply and demand dynamics.</p></li>
        <li><p><b>Liquidity:</b> They provide liquidity, enabling investors to easily buy or sell assets without significant price impact.</p></li>
        <li><p><b>Capital Allocation:</b> Financial markets facilitate the allocation of capital by channeling funds from savers to borrowers or companies in need of financing.</p></li>
        <li><p><b>Risk Management:</b> They offer risk management tools, such as derivatives, allowing investors to hedge against market fluctuations.</p></li>
        <li><p><b>Investor Protection: </b>Financial markets operate under regulatory frameworks that aim to protect investors' interests and ensure fair trading practices.</p></li>
        </ul>
        
        <h4>Market Participants</h4>
    
        <ul>
        <li><p>Individual Investors</p></li>
        <li><p>Institutional Investors (banks, pension funds, insurance companies)</p></li>
        <li><p>Trader</p></li>
        <li><p>Brokers and Dealers</p></li>
        <li><p>Exchanges</p></li>
        <li><p>Regulatory Authorities</p></li>
        </ul>
        
        <h4>Importance of Financial Markets</h4>
        
        <p class="indent">Financial markets play a vital role in the economy by:</p>
        
        <ul>
        <li><p>Facilitating capital formation and economic growth</p></li>
        <li><p>Providing opportunities for investments and wealth creation</p></li>
        <li><p>Enabling efficient allocation of resources</p></li>
        <li><p>Supporting risk management and hedging strategies</p></li>
        <li><p>Contributing to price stability and economic stability</p></li>
        </ul>
        
        <p>Understanding financial markets is crucial for investors and participants to make informed decisions and navigate the complexities of the global financial system.</p>
       </section>
