       <section id="emt">
    
        <h2>Types of Financial Market</h2>
        <ul>
        <li>
        <h3>By the Nature of the Claim:</h3>
        
        <ul>
        <li>
        <h5> Equity Market: </h5><p>Involves buying and selling shares of publicly traded companies. Example: Buying shares of Tesla Inc. on the NASDAQ stock exchange with the expectation of capital appreciation.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
        <h5> Debt Market: </h5><p> Involves buying and selling of debt securities issued by governments and corporations. Example: Investing in US Treasury bonds to earn fixed interest income or purchasing corporate bonds issued by IBM Corporation.</p>
        </li>
        </ul>
        </li>
        <li>
        <ul>
        <h3>By the Maturity on Claim:</h3>
        <li>
        <h4>Short Tenure (less than 1 year)</h4>
        
        <h5>Money Market:</h5><p class="indent"> Deals with short-term borrowing and lending of funds, typically for periods of one year or less. It includes instruments such as Treasury bills, certificates of deposit, commercial paper, and repurchase agreements. Example: Investing in a 3-month Treasury bill issued by the government.</p>
        
        
        <li>
        <h4>Longer Maturity (more than 1 year)</h4>
        
        <ul>
        <li>
        <h5>Capital Market:</h5><p class="indent"> Deals with long-term borrowing and lending of funds, typically for periods exceeding one year.
        </p></li>
        <li>
        <h5>Equity Market:</h5><p class="indent"> Involves the buying and selling of shares of publicly traded companies. Example: Purchasing shares of Apple Inc. on the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE)</p>.
        </li>
        <li>
        <h5>Bond Market:</h5> <p class="indent">Involves the buying and selling of debt securities issued by governments and corporations. Example: Investing in corporate bonds issued by Microsoft Corporation.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
        <h5>Real Estate Market:</h5> <p class="indent">Involves the buying, selling, and renting of properties such as residential and commercial buildings. Example: Buying a residential property for investment purposes or renting an office space for business operations.</p>
        </li>
        </ul>
        </li>
        </li>
        </ul>
        <li>
        <h3>Based on the Organisational Structure:</h3>
        
        <ul>
        <li>
        <h5>Exchange-Traded Market:</h5><p class="indent"> A marketplace where people can buy and sell financial products like stocks, bonds, commodities, and derivatives. It's a centralized location with regulated and organized trading. Prices are public, and fair trading practices are ensured. Examples include stock exchanges and commodity exchanges.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
        <h5>Over the Counter Market (OTC):</h5><p class="indent"> A decentralized marketplace where trading happens directly between two parties without a central exchange. Buyers and sellers negotiate and trade through phone, email, or electronic platforms.</p>
        </li>
        </ul>
        </li>
        <li>
        <h3>Based on the timing of delivery:</h3>
        
        <ul>
        <li>
        <h5>Cash Market (Spot Market):</h5><p class="indent"> Financial instruments are bought and sold for immediate delivery and payment. Transactions are settled "on the spot," meaning the buyer pays and the seller delivers the asset immediately. This market deals with the immediate exchange of goods or securities for cash at the current market price.</p> <p>Example: Cash market transactions occur when you buy fruits, vegetables, or any other product at a grocery store by paying cash.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
        <h5>Futures Market:</h5><p class="indent"> Involves trading standardized contracts called futures contracts. These contracts specify the delivery of an underlying asset at a predetermined future date and price. Parties involved agree to buy or sell the asset on a specified future date, regardless of the current market price at that time. Futures contracts are traded on exchanges with standardized terms and conditions (including quantity, quality, and delivery date).</p> <p>Example: A farmer entering a futures contract to sell a certain quantity of corn to a buyer at a predetermined price and delivery date. The transaction will be settled at the agreed-upon future date, regardless of the current market price of corn.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
        <h5>Foreign Exchange Market</h5>
        <p class="indent">The Foreign Exchange Market facilitates the buying and selling of different currencies. It allows individuals, businesses, and financial institutions to exchange one currency for another, enabling international trade and investment.  Imagine exchanging US Dollars (USD) for Euros (EUR) before a trip to Europe.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
        <h5>Commodity Market</h5>
        <p class="indent">The Commodity Market deals with buying and selling of raw materials like gold, oil, agricultural products, and industrial metals.  Here, you might purchase gold bullion as a hedge against inflation or trade contracts for crude oil futures.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
        <h5>Cryptocurrency Market</h5>
        <p class="indent">The Cryptocurrency Market involves buying and selling digital currencies like Bitcoin, Ethereum, and others. These cryptocurrencies operate on decentralized networks using blockchain technology, allowing secure and direct transactions between individuals (peer-to-peer).  An example is buying Bitcoin (BTC) or Ethereum (ETH).</p>
            </li>
        </ul>
        </li>
        </ul>
    </section>
    
    <section id="wcm">
      <h2>Capital Market</h2>
<p>The capital market is a financial market where long-term securities such as stocks and bonds are bought and sold. It facilitates the transfer of capital from investors to businesses or governments in need of funding for various purposes.</p>

<h3>Types of Capital Market</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<h4>Primary Market</h4>
<p>The primary market is where new securities are issued and sold for the first time. It allows companies and governments to raise fresh capital by selling stocks or bonds directly to investors.</p>
</li>
<li>
<h4>Secondary Market</h4>
<p>The secondary market is where previously issued securities are traded among investors. It provides liquidity to investors by allowing them to buy or sell existing securities without involving the issuing companies.</p>
</li>
</ul>

<h3>Functions of Capital Market</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><b>Facilitating Capital Formation: </b>The capital market enables businesses and governments to raise funds for investment and expansion by issuing securities to interested investors.</p></li>
<li><p><b>Providing Liquidity:</b> The secondary market allows investors to buy and sell securities, providing liquidity and ensuring the marketability of investments.</p></li>
<li><p><b>Price Determination: </b>Capital markets facilitate the discovery of fair prices for securities through the forces of supply and demand.</p></li>
<li><p><b>Risk Transfer:</b> Investors can transfer their investment risks by buying and selling securities in the capital market.</p></li>
<li><p><b>Investor Protection: </b>Capital markets often have regulations and mechanisms in place to protect the interests of investors and maintain market integrity.</p></li>
</ul>
  </section>
  <section id="pm"><h2>Primary Market</h2>

<p>The primary market, also known as the new issue market, is where securities are issued and sold for the first time by companies or governments to raise capital. It is the initial offering of securities to the public.</p>

<h3>Functions of the Primary Market</h3>

<ul>
<li><p><b>Raising Capital:</b> The primary market enables companies to raise funds for business expansion, project financing, debt repayment, research and development, and other capital requirements.</p></li>
<li><p><b>Facilitating Ownership Transfer:</b> Through the primary market, ownership of a company is transferred from private ownership to public ownership by issuing shares to the general public.</p></li>
<li><p><b>Price Discovery:</b> The primary market helps in determining the initial price of securities based on market demand and investor appetite, establishing the fair value of the securities.</p></li>
<li><p><b>Increasing Market Liquidity:</b> By listing on the primary market, companies provide an opportunity for investors to buy and sell their shares, increasing market liquidity.</p></li>
<li>
<p><b>Underwriting: </b>
Involves an agreement where an underwriter, typically a financial institution, guarantees the sale of a company's shares by purchasing the unsold shares or finding buyers for them.</p>
</li>
</ul>

<h3>Types of Primary Market Offerings</h3>

<ul>
<li><p><b>Initial Public Offering (IPO):</b> An IPO is the first sale of securities by a company to the public. It allows companies to raise capital and become publicly traded entities.</p></li>
<li><p><b>Follow-on Public Offering (FPO):</b> An FPO is a subsequent offering of securities by a company that is already listed on the stock exchange. It helps companies raise additional capital for expansion or other purposes.</p></li>
<li><p><b>Rights Issue:</b> A rights issue allows existing shareholders to purchase additional shares of the company at a discounted price in proportion to their existing holdings.</p></li>
<li><p><b>Private Placement:</b> Private placement involves the sale of securities directly to institutional investors or a select group of investors, bypassing the public offering process.</p></li>
<li><p><b>Qualified Institutional Placement (QIP):</b> A QIP is a private placement of securities exclusively to qualified institutional buyers, such as banks, financial institutions, and mutual funds.</p></li>
</ul>
  </section>
  <section id="sm">
<h2>Secondary Market</h2>

<p>The secondary market, also known as the stock market or stock exchange, is where already issued securities are bought and sold among investors. It provides a platform for trading previously issued securities.</p>

<h3>Examples of Secondary Market</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><b>Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE):</b> It is one of the oldest stock exchanges in Asia and the largest stock exchange in India.</p></li>
<li><p><b>National Stock Exchange (NSE):</b> It is the leading stock exchange in India that provides a modern, fully automated trading platform.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3>Functions of the Secondary Market</h3>

<ul>
<li><p><b>Liquidity:</b> The secondary market provides liquidity to investors, allowing them to buy or sell securities at any time, based on supply and demand.</p></li>
<li><p><b> Determination:</b> It helps in determining the fair market price of securities based on the forces of supply and demand.</p></li>
<li><p><b>Facilitating Trading:</b> The secondary market facilitates the buying and selling of securities through various trading mechanisms, such as stock exchanges and electronic trading platforms.</p></li>
<li><p><b>Investment Opportunities:</b> It provides opportunities for investors to diversify their portfolios and invest in a wide range of securities, including stocks, bonds, derivatives, and exchange-traded funds.</p>
</ul>

<h3>Types of Secondary Market</h3>

