 <section id="ratio">
     <h2>Ratios</h2>
     <ol>
         <li>
             <h5><b>Return on Assets (ROA)</b></h5>
             <p><b>Definition:</b> ROA measures how efficiently a company utilizes its assets to generate profits. It indicates the percentage of each rupee of assets that generates net income.</p>
             <p><b>Formula:</b> <em>ROA = (Net Income / Average Total Assets) x 100</em></p>
             <p><b>Uses:</b> ROA helps assess the profitability and efficiency of asset utilization. Higher ROA indicates better performance. For example, a company with an ROA of 15% means it generates ₹0.15 of net income for every rupee of assets invested.</p>
         </li>
         <li>
             <h5><b>Return on Investment (ROI)</b></h5>
             <p><b>Definition:</b> ROI evaluates the return on an investment relative to its cost. It shows the percentage gain or loss on an investment.</p>
             <p><b>Formula:</b> <em>ROI = (Net Profit / Cost of Investment) x 100</em></p>
             <p><b>Uses:</b> ROI helps assess the profitability of an investment. It enables comparison between different investment options. For example, if an investment of ₹10,000 generates a net profit of ₹2,000, the ROI would be 20%, indicating a 20% return on the investment.</p>
         </li>
         <li>
             <h5><b>Gross Margin Ratio</b></h5>
             <p><b>Definition:</b> The gross margin ratio indicates the profitability of a company's core operations by measuring the percentage of revenue that remains after deducting the cost of goods sold.</p>
             <p><b>Formula:</b> <em>Gross Margin Ratio = (Gross Profit / Revenue) x 100</em></p>
             <p><b>Uses:</b> The gross margin ratio helps assess the profitability of a company's products or services. Higher gross margin ratio implies better profitability. For example, if a company has a gross margin ratio of 40%, it means it retains ₹0.40 as gross profit for every rupee of revenue generated.</p>
         </li>
         <li>
             <h5><b>Operating Margin Ratio</b></h5>
             <p><b>Definition:</b> The operating margin ratio assesses a company's operating efficiency and profitability by measuring the percentage of each rupee of revenue that translates into operating income.</p>
             <p><b>Formula:</b> <em>Operating Margin Ratio = (Operating Income / Revenue) x 100</em></p>
             <p><b>Uses:</b> The operating margin ratio helps evaluate the profitability of a company's core operations. Higher operating margin ratio indicates better operating efficiency. For example, if a company has an operating margin ratio of 15%, it means it generates ₹0.15 of operating income for every rupee of revenue earned.</p>
         </li>
         <li>
             <h5><b>Debt-to-Equity Ratio</b></h5>
             <p><b>Definition:</b> The debt-to-equity ratio evaluates a company's capital structure and financial leverage by comparing its total debt to shareholders' equity.</p>
             <p><b>Formula:</b> <em>Debt-to-Equity Ratio = Total Debt / Shareholders' Equity</em></p>
             <p><b>Uses:</b> The debt-to-equity ratio helps assess a company's financial risk and solvency. It indicates the proportion of financing provided by debt and equity. A lower ratio is generally preferred, as it signifies a lower risk of financial distress. For example, if a company has a debt-to-equity ratio of 0.8, it means it has ₹0.80 of debt for every rupee of shareholders' equity.</p>
         </li>
         <li>
             <h5><b>Current Ratio</b></h5>
             <p><b>Definition:</b> The current ratio measures a company's ability to meet its short-term obligations using its current assets.</p>
             <p><b>Formula:</b> <em>Current Ratio = Current Assets / Current Liabilities</em></p>
             <p><b>Use:</b> The current ratio helps assess a company's short-term liquidity. A ratio of 2 or higher is generally considered favorable, indicating a strong ability to cover short-term obligations. For example, if a company has current assets of ₹1,00,000 and current liabilities of ₹50,000, the current ratio would be 2, indicating a healthy liquidity position.</p>
         </li>
         <li>
             <h5><b>Earnings Per Share (EPS)</b></h5>
             <p><b>Definition:</b> EPS measures the portion of a company's profit allocated to each outstanding share of common stock.</p>
             <p><b>Formula:</b> <em>EPS = (Net Income - Preferred Dividends) / Average Outstanding Shares</em></p>
             <p><b>Use:</b> EPS helps assess a company's profitability on a per-share basis. Higher EPS indicates higher profitability. For example, if a company has a net income of ₹5,00,000, preferred dividends of ₹50,000, and 1,00,000 outstanding shares, the EPS would be ₹4.50 (₹4.50 per share).</p>
         </li>
         <li>
             <h5><b>Price-to-Earnings Ratio (P/E Ratio)</b></h5>
             <p><b>Definition:</b> The P/E ratio compares a company's stock price to its earnings per share, indicating the market's valuation of the company.</p>
             <p><b>Formula:</b> <em>P/E Ratio = Market Price per Share / Earnings Per Share</em></p>
             <p><b>Use:</b> The P/E ratio helps assess a company's valuation relative to its earnings. Higher P/E ratios generally imply higher market expectations. For example, if a company's stock is trading at ₹100 per share and has an EPS of ₹5, the P/E ratio would be 20x (20 times earnings).</p>
         </li>
         <li>
             <h5><b>Dividend Yield</b></h5>
             <p><b>Definition:</b> Dividend Yield measures the return on investment from dividends distributed by a company.</p>
             <p><b>Formula:</b> <em>Dividend Yield = (Dividends per Share / Market Price per Share) x 100</em></p>
             <p><b>Use:</b> Dividend Yield helps assess the income generated from dividends relative to the stock price. Higher dividend yield indicates higher returns from dividends. For example, if a company pays dividends of ₹10 per share and its stock is trading at ₹200 per share, the dividend yield would be 5%.</p>
         </li>
