<h2>Intrinsic Value Calculation</h2>
<h4>Definition</h4>
<p>Intrinsic value represents the present value of the expected future cash flows generated by a company, adjusted for the time value of money and the perceived risk associated with the investment.</p>

<h4>Formula (DCF method)</h4>
<p>
<i>Intrinsic Value = (CF1 / (1+r)^1) + (CF2 / (1+r)^2) + ... + (CFn / (1+r)^n)</i>
</p>
<p>
Where:

CF1, CF2, ..., CFn = Expected future cash flows for each period (usually years)
r = Discount rate, representing the desired rate of return or the minimum acceptable return for the investment
</p>
<p>Example
Let's assume a company is expected to generate the following annual cash flows over the next five years: ₹10,000, ₹15,000, ₹20,000, ₹25,000, and ₹30,000. The discount rate is determined to be 10%.
</p>

    <p><i>Intrinsic Value = (₹10,000 / (1+0.10)^1) + (₹15,000 / (1+0.10)^2) + (₹20,000 / (1+0.10)^3) + (₹25,000 / (1+0.10)^4) + (₹30,000 / (1+0.10)^5)</i>

    </p><p><i>
    Intrinsic Value = ₹9,090.91 + ₹12,396.69 + ₹16,530.00 + ₹20,752.89 + ₹24,835.86
    </i></p>
    <p><i>
    Intrinsic Value = ₹83,606.45
    </i></p>
<p>Based on the DCF analysis, the intrinsic value of the company's stock is estimated to be ₹83,606.45. If the current market price of the stock is significantly lower than the calculated intrinsic value, it may indicate that the stock is undervalued and potentially a good investment opportunity.</p>

