  <h2>Financial Statements</h2>
    <p><strong>Definition:</strong> Financial statements are formal records that present the financial activities and performance of a company. They provide an overview of a company's financial position, results of operations, and cash flows.</p>

    <h3>Types of Financial Statements</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>
            <h4>Income Statement</h4>
            <p>
                Also known as the profit and loss statement.
                Shows the company's revenues, expenses, and net income or loss over a specific period.
                Helps assess the company's profitability.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <h4>Balance Sheet</h4>
            <p>
                Provides a snapshot of the company's financial position at a specific point in time.
                Presents the company's assets, liabilities, and shareholders' equity, helping evaluate its solvency and financial strength.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <h4>Cash Flow Statement</h4>
            <p>
                Shows the inflows and outflows of cash and cash equivalents during a specific period.
                Helps assess the company's liquidity and cash management.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <h4>Statement of Changes in Equity</h4>
            <p>
                Tracks the changes in shareholders' equity over a specific period.
                Includes details of share capital, retained earnings, and other equity components.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Uses of Financial Statements</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><p>Assessing the financial performance and profitability of a company</p></li>
        <li><p>Evaluating the company's liquidity and cash flow position</p></li>
        <li><p>Assessing the company's financial health and solvency</p></li>
        <li><p>Comparing the company's financial performance with industry benchmarks</p></li>
        <li><p>Assisting in investment decision-making and valuation</p></li>
        <li><p>Providing information to stakeholders, such as investors, lenders, and regulatory authorities</p></li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Example Format for Identifying Financial Statements</h3>
    <table>
        <tr>
            <th>Financial Statement</th>
            <th>Format</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Income Statement</td>
            <td><strong>Revenue - Expenses = Net Income</strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Balance Sheet</td>
            <td><strong>Assets = Liabilities + Shareholders' Equity</strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Cash Flow Statement</td>
            <td><strong>Cash from Operating Activities + Cash from Investing Activities + Cash from Financing Activities = Net Increase/Decrease in Cash</strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Statement of Changes in Equity</td>
            <td><strong>Beginning Shareholders' Equity + Net Income/Loss + Additional Investments - Dividends = Ending Shareholders' Equity</strong></td>
        </tr>
    </table>
